SIMPLE: limbus
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Limbus
<hw>Lim"bus</hw>
<pr>(l⟦icr⟧m"b⟦ucr⟧s)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>limbus</ets> border, edge <ets>in limbo</ets> on the border. Cf.
<er>Limb</er> border.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Scholastic Theol.)</fld>
<def>An spiritual region where certain classes of souls were supposed to
await the last judgment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As far from help as <qex>Limbo</qex> is from bliss.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>Limbo</qex> large and broad, since called⟦br⟧
The Paradise of fools.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The <xex>limbus patrum</xex> was considered as a place
for the souls of good men who lived before the coming of our Savior. The
<xex>limbus infantium</xex> was said to be a similar place for the souls
of unbaptized infants. To these was added, in the popular belief, the
<xex>limbus fatuorum</xex>, or fool's paradise, regarded as a receptacle
of all vanity and nonsense.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence: Any real or imaginary place of restraint or
confinement; a prison; <as>as, to put a man in
<ex>limbo</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>A state of waiting, or
uncertainty, in which final judgment concerning the outcome of a
decision is postponed, perhaps indefinitely; neglect for an indefinite
time; <as>as, the proposal was left in <ex>limbo</ex> while opponents
and proponents refused to compromise</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A border or margin; <as>as, the
<ex>limbus</ex> of the cornea</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Limbo</ent>⟦br⟧
